<subSubSection id="01BB5B980EDF28473483934A3F06DA99" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comments">
<paragraph id="3F81C47809BE8721C3BC9B16C7412611" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6D369BEA4E7D9F083621FB3C970AD755" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="0DFF704D236C2B90F56C9A7559F5BA6F" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophiomyia tiliae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tiliae">
<emphasis id="BE5F2CBF2D088171AD2A4DA0EC55C1E0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ophiomyia tiliae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is much darker than similar species such as 
<taxonomicName id="D63E180EF89EE6069930687F133656F6" family="Agromyzidae" genus="O." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="O. abutilivora" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="abutilivora">
<emphasis id="9E1E1EBE66D0424CB533853AD99FB589" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">O. abutilivora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and often has a much higher gena. An ovate distiphallus with a ventrally directed apical flagellum and bordered by a wide transverse sclerite are most diagnostic.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9D1BB3A23F01ED3A88DB98ADA68FDB6F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="1FC8B727EBA223ADC9ED27E0CB13004F" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1969" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophiomyia fastosa" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fastosa">
<emphasis id="866713940446E77CDA5055751A65004A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ophiomyia fastosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
syn. nov. is here included as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="277520662B60327431F3489294802C8D" family="Agromyzidae" genus="O." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="O. tiliae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="tiliae">
<emphasis id="092E122C04D5E5E4FA7C0C68EB76CB97" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">O. tiliae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which overlaps in wing length, gena height, colour and chaetotaxy. Morphology of the surstylus/epandrium are also similar, as is morphology of the phallus, with variations seen in previously published illustrations of the distiphallus being strongly exaggerated or not evident upon re-examination.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D3675673408E9196A21381CB8F082207" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Male genitalic illustration of 
<taxonomicName id="3868DC331A0AD9A5979A629F74E3167E" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1973" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophiomyia parvella" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parvella">
<emphasis id="EE3BB1D74F6EB0EB45B4216D62F36C51" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ophiomyia parvella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Spencer (
<bibRefCitation id="7B63412A14E9D9F3D6652F3716E9BB96" author="Spencer, KA" journalOrPublisher=")" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B259" refString="Spencer, KA, Stegmaier, Jr CE, 1973. The Agromyzidae of Florida with a supplement on Species from the Caribbean. Arthropods of Florida 7: iv + 205." title="The Agromyzidae of Florida with a supplement on Species from the Caribbean. Arthropods of Florida 7: iv + 205." year="1973">Spencer and Stegmaier 1973</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="F05C96CA4EF4A71425524599AFC1AB39" author="Sasakawa, M" journalOrPublisher="Agriculture" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="15 - 41" refId="B214" refString="Sasakawa, M, 1994. The Neotropical Agromyzidae (Diptera): Part 5. New or little-known species from Chile Scientific Reports of the Kyoto Prefectural University. Agriculture 46: 15 - 41" title="The Neotropical Agromyzidae (Diptera): Part 5. New or little-known species from Chile Scientific Reports of the Kyoto Prefectural University." volume="46" year="1994">Sasakawa 1994</bibRefCitation>
) almost exactly matches the genitalia of 
<taxonomicName id="77853A60ABCE8B094689A19F2864BD57" family="Agromyzidae" genus="O." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="O. tiliae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="tiliae">
<emphasis id="EE943CBE3034AEC12854D66185E2681B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">O. tiliae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and may also be conspecific. While the host of 
<taxonomicName id="F236905055B58A212F3232FB9F9FD4AD" family="Agromyzidae" genus="O." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="O. parvella" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="parvella">
<emphasis id="7BCCBF50B97A318D58C606D8A3C7515C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">O. parvella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unknown, the host of 
<taxonomicName id="7BB8A4F5B4EB3CC714E03050E3E1E4E5" family="Agromyzidae" genus="O." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="O. tiliae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="tiliae">
<emphasis id="F0C4B1BA7D7E20316BEBFBCD56B8D529" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">O. tiliae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="D14E115A8DB98EB515062B3454E6B1C8" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Tilia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tilia americana" order="Malvales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="americana">
<emphasis id="55C309AADD15F2AABBB29B6710E53284" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Tilia americana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, American basswood is found in Florida (
<bibRefCitation id="BAD1805258ACF852148A233BEDE846F3" author="USDA" journalOrPublisher="Feddes Repertorium, Berlin" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" publicationUrl="https://plants.usda.gov/" refId="B275" refString="USDA, 2008. Natural Resources Conservation Service: Plants Database. https://plants.usda.gov/" title="Natural Resources Conservation Service: Plants Database." url="https://plants.usda.gov/" year="2008">USDA 2008</bibRefCitation>
), where 
<taxonomicName id="CE3413926433AC0C16BA92083428E2D9" family="Agromyzidae" genus="O." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="O. parvella" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="parvella">
<emphasis id="CBAA2731BC6750CA8DDA9DB7C604AD97" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">O. parvella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from. 
<taxonomicName id="E7A3168FB60D9BCF56CF38AF23969C21" authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1981" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophiomyia shastensis" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="shastensis">
<emphasis id="195058947B6C0852DCCCD3C1B57732F5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ophiomyia shastensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Spencer has highly similar genitalia, but apparently differs from 
<taxonomicName id="083BE22F36B27B066A6DA9D611020BF1" family="Agromyzidae" genus="O." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="O. tiliae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="tiliae">
<emphasis id="D1F604B9AAA02B528610896894B5FBD0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">O. tiliae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a metallic abdomen; the metallic tint is evident in some specimens examined here, including those in the northeast, suggesting that the boundaries of this species require future re-examination.
</paragraph>
